    <p>
      Johannes Kepler established three laws for planetary motion from his 
      years of observation in <m>16^{th}</m> century [<xref ref="kepler1"/>]. They are 
      <ol>
        <li>
          The planets move along elliptical paths, and the sun is located at one of the focii.
        </li>
        <li>
          The planet sweeps out equal areas in equal interval of time 
          <me>
            \frac{\,dA_{1}}{\,dt} = \frac{\,dA_{2}}{\,dt}
          </me>
           </li>
           <li>
            The square of the orbital period of a planet is directly proportional to the cube of the semimajor axis of its orbit 
            <me>
              T^{2} \propto a^{3}.
            </me>
             </li>
      </ol>
    </p>
   </introduction>

   <subsection xml:id="subsec-periap">
    <title>Periapsis and Apoapsis:</title>
    <p>
      The asymmetric position of a massive object within the elliptical orbit renders 
      the orbiting object moves in a varying distance from the massive object. 
      The distance of closest approach <m>d_{1}</m> is called the periapsis and the distance 
      of maximum separation, <m>d_{2} </m> is called the apoapsis. For the earth around 
      the sun perihelion is the distance of closest approach and "aphelion" is distance 
      of the maximum separation (helio means sun in Greek) [<xref ref="kepler2"/>]. For earth-moon system, 
      "perigee" is the distance of closest approach and "apogee" is distance of the 
      maximum separation (gee means earth in Greek). 
    </p>

    <paragraphs>
      <title>Derivation of Kepler's III law using Newton's law of gravitation:</title>
      <p>
        A planet moving around a circular path needs a centripetal force which is provided 
        by the force of attraction between the planet and the sun. 
        <me>
          F=\frac{GMm}{r^{2}}=\frac{mv^{2}}{r}
        </me>
        where <m>M,\quad m,</m> and <m>r</m> are the mass of the sun, 
        mass of the planet, and radius of a circular path, respectively.
      <men xml:id="eqn-kepler1">
        \therefore\quad v=\sqrt{\frac{GM}{r}} 
      </men>
     But, the velocity of the planet in the orbit is given by 
     <men xml:id="eqn-kepler2">
      v=\frac{2\pi r}{T} 
     </men>
   where <m>T</m> is the time period of revolution of the planet around the sun. 
   <me>
    \therefore\quad \frac{4\pi^{2} r^{2}}{T^{2}} = \frac{GM}{r}
   </me>
   <me>
    \text{or,}\quad T^{2} = r^{3}\left(\frac{4\pi^{2}}{GM}\right)
   </me>
   <me>
    \text{or,}\quad  T^{2}\propto r^{3}
   </me>
    </p>
    </paragraphs>

    <paragraphs>
      <title>Derivation of Kepler's II law</title>
      <p>
        If planet is considered at very close to the semimajor axis, so that point 
        <m>P</m> is very close to point <m>O</m>, then from <m>\triangle PSO</m> [<xref ref="kepler2"/>], we have -  
        <me>
          \Delta A =\frac{1}{2}base\times height = \frac{1}{2}(r)(r \Delta \theta)
        </me>
        where height = <m>r\Delta \theta </m>  and base = <m>r</m> for the triangle. 
        <me>
          \therefore \frac{\Delta A}{\Delta t} = \frac{1}{2}r^{2}\frac{\Delta \theta}{\Delta t} =\frac{1}{2}r^{2}\omega 
        </me>
        For small time <m>\Delta t</m> consider angle subtends by the earth is <m>\Delta \theta.</m>
        Now, angular momentum of the planet, 
        <me>
          L=I\omega = mr^{2}\omega 
        </me>
        <me>
          \therefore\quad \frac{\Delta A}{\Delta t} =\frac{1}{2}\frac{L}{m}
        </me>
        <me>
          \frac{\,dA}{\,dt}=constant 
        </me>
       since angular momentum  of a planet in an orbit and its mass remains constant.
      </p>
    </paragraphs>

    <paragraphs>
      <title>Derivation of Kepler's I law</title>
      <p>
        <me>
          F=ma=-\frac{GMm}{r^{2}}
        </me>
        <men xml:id="eqn-kepler3">
          \text{or,}\quad \ddot{r}-r\dot{\theta}^{2}=-\frac{GM}{r^{2}}  
        </men>
       <me>
        x=r\cos\theta, \qquad y=r\sin\theta
       </me>
       <me>
        \dot{x}=\dot{r}\cos\theta -r\sin\theta\dot{\theta},
       </me>
       <me>
        \dot{y}=\dot{r}\sin\theta +r\cos\theta\dot{\theta}
       </me>
       <me>
        v^{2}=\dot{x}^{2}+\dot{y}^{2} = \dot{r}^{2}+r^{2}\dot{\theta}^{2}
       </me>
       <me>
        \ddot{x}=\ddot{r}\cos\theta -\dot{r}\dot{\theta}\sin\theta -\dot{r}\dot{\theta}\sin\theta -r\dot{\theta}^{2}\cos\theta-r\ddot{\theta}\sin\theta, 
       </me>
       <me>
        \ddot{y}=\ddot{r}\sin\theta +\dot{r}\dot{\theta}\cos\theta +\dot{r}\dot{\theta}\cos\theta -r\dot{\theta}^{2}\sin\theta+r\ddot{\theta}\cos\theta
       </me>
    Now, 
    <md>
      <mrow> a\amp =\ddot{x}\cos\theta+\ddot{y}\sin\theta </mrow>
      <mrow> \amp =(\ddot{r}\cos^{2}\theta -2\dot{r}\dot{\theta}\sin\theta\cos\theta -r\dot{\theta}^{2}\cos^{2}\theta-r\ddot{\theta}\sin\theta\cos\theta) </mrow>
      <mrow> \amp  +(\ddot{r}\sin^{2}\theta +2\dot{r}\dot{\theta}\sin\theta\cos\theta -r\dot{\theta}^{2}\sin^{2}\theta+r\ddot{\theta}\sin\theta\cos\theta) </mrow>
     <mrow> \amp  =\ddot{r}-r\dot{\theta}^{2} </mrow>
    </md>
      </p>
      <p>
        Let 
        <me>
          \frac{1}{r}=u 
        </me>
     so that
        <me>
          \dot{r}=-r^{2}\dot{u} =-r^{2}\frac{\,du}{\,d\theta}\dot{\theta}
        </me>
        Also, 
        <me>
          L=mr^{2}\dot{\theta}\quad \Rightarrow\quad \dot{\theta}= \frac{L}{mr^{2}}=hu^{2}
        </me>
      Now, 
      <me>
        \dot{r}=-r^{2}\frac{\,du}{\,d\theta} hu^{2}=-h\frac{\,du}{\,d\theta}
      </me>
      Therefore from eqn <xref ref="eqn-kepler3"/>,
      <me>
        \frac{\,d}{\,dt}\left(\dot{r}\right) -r(hu^{2})^{2}=-GMu^{2}
      </me>
      <me>
        \text{or,}\quad \frac{\,d}{\,dt}\left(-h\frac{\,du}{\,d\theta}\right) -h^{2}u^{3}=-ku^{2} 
      </me>
      <me>
        \text{or,}\quad -h\left[\frac{\,d\theta}{\,dt}\frac{\,d}{\,d\theta}\left(\frac{\,du}{\,d\theta}\right)\right] -h^{2}u^{3}=-ku^{2} 
      </me>
      <me>
        \text{or,}\quad -h\left[hu^{2}\frac{\,d^{2}u}{\,d\theta^{2}}\right] -h^{2}u^{3}=-ku^{2} 
      </me>
      <men xml:id="eqn-kepler4">
        \therefore\quad  \frac{\,d^{2}u}{\,d\theta^{2}} +u=\frac{k}{h^{2}} 
      </men>
    This is second order linear differential equation with constant coefficient. 
    The solution of which can be given as 
    <me>
      u=A\cos(\theta+\delta)+\frac{k}{h^{2}} 
    </me>
    It is a solution for a simple harmonic motion equation. Set the coordinate in such a 
    way that <m>\delta=0,</m> and hence 
    <me>
      u=\frac{1}{r} = A\cos\theta+\frac{k}{h^{2}}
    </me>
   <me>
    \text{or,}\quad r=\frac{1}{A\cos\theta+\frac{k}{h^{2}}} =\frac{1}{A\cos\theta+\frac{GMm^{2}}{L^{2}}}
   </me> 
   <men xml:id="eqn-kepler5">
    \therefore\quad r=\frac{1}{\frac{GMm^{2}}{L^{2}}\left(e\cos\theta+1\right)}
   </men>
   where <m> e= \frac{AL^{2}}{GMm^{2}}</m>
  Eqn. <xref ref="eqn-kepler5"/> is the general form of an ellipse in polar coordinates, 
  with the origin placed at a focus. In solid state geometry, the parameter <m>e</m> is 
  often called the eccentricity. When the eccentricity of a planet's orbit is zero, 
  the orbit is perfectly circular. The curve is an ellipse, a parabola, or a hyperbola, 
  according as its <m>e \lt 1, </m> <m>e = 1, </m> or <m>e \gt 1. </m>
  <me>
    \therefore \quad a=\frac{1}{2}\left(r_{min}+r_{max}\right)
  </me>
  <me>
    =\frac{L^{2}}{GMm^{2}}\left(\frac{1}{e+1}+\frac{1}{1-e}\right)= \frac{L^{2}}{GMm^{2}}\left(1-e^{2}\right)^{-1} 
  </me>
  where <m>a</m> is a semi-major axis of the ellipse, at apoapsis, <m>\cos\theta=-1 </m> and at periapsis <m>\cos\theta=1.</m>

     </p>
    </paragraphs>
